events.description: The benchmark index rose 0.3% to close at 13,467 on Wednesday.
China released its January composite and service PMI data, both reaching three-month highs.
Local data showed unemployment rising to 5.4% while employment growth increased to 0.5%.
Investors are awaiting US employment data due later in the day.

facts.fact_text: New Zealand’s benchmark S&P/NZX 50 rose 0.3% to close at 13,467 on Wednesday.

evidences.evidence_text: New Zealand’s benchmark S&P/NZX 50 rose 0.3% to close at 13,467 on Wednesday

facts.fact_text: China's January composite PMI was 51.6 and its service PMI was 52.3.

evidences.evidence_text: release of its January composite PMI at a three-month high of 51.6 and a service PMI also at a three-month peak of 52.3

facts.fact_text: The New Zealand Q4 unemployment rate rose to 5.4% from 5.3%.

evidences.evidence_text: Q4 unemployment rate edged up to 5.4% from 5.3% in the previous quarter

facts.fact_text: New Zealand employment growth was 0.5% in Q4.

evidences.evidence_text: employment growth picked up to 0.5% after remaining flat in Q3

claims.claim_text: Market sentiment was lifted by positive economic data from China.

evidences.evidence_text: Sentiment was lifted by China, New Zealand’s top trading partner, following the release of its January composite PMI

claims.claim_text: The mixed jobs report put downward pressure on the New Zealand dollar.

evidences.evidence_text: The mixed jobs report weighed on the local dollar

claims.claim_text: The jobs report provided support for exporters and stabilized sectors sensitive to interest rates.
